# apache-flink Best Practices

## Code Organization and Structure

### Use Immutable Configuration Objects
Always use immutable configuration objects for your Flink jobs. This ensures thread-safety and avoids unexpected mutations.

❌ BAD
```java
public class JobConfig {
    public String inputPath;
    public String outputPath;
}
```

✅ GOOD
```java
public final class JobConfig {
    private final String inputPath;
    private final String outputPath;

    public JobConfig(String inputPath, String outputPath) {
        this.inputPath = inputPath;
        this.outputPath = outputPath;
    }

    public String getInputPath() {
        return inputPath;
    }

    public String getOutputPath() {
        return outputPath;
    }
}
```

### Constructor Injection for Dependencies
Pass dependencies through constructors to maintain a clean separation of concerns. This makes your code easier to test and maintain.

❌ BAD
```java
public class DataProcessor {
    private DatabaseService databaseService;

    public void initialize() {
        this.databaseService = new DatabaseService();
    }
}
```

✅ GOOD
```java
public class DataProcessor {
    private final DatabaseService databaseService;

    public DataProcessor(DatabaseService databaseService) {
        this.databaseService = databaseService;
    }
}
```

## Common Patterns and Anti-patterns

### Use RocksDB for Large Stateful Jobs
For stateful jobs exceeding 1GB, leverage RocksDB to manage state efficiently and avoid JVM memory pressure.

❌ BAD
```java
StreamExecutionEnvironment env = StreamExecutionEnvironment.getExecutionEnvironment();
env.setStateBackend(new MemoryStateBackend());
```

✅ GOOD
```java
StreamExecutionEnvironment env = StreamExecutionEnvironment.getExecutionEnvironment();
env.setStateBackend(new RocksDBStateBackend("s3://my-bucket/flink-checkpoints"));
```

### Implement Operator UIDs
Always set UIDs for your operators to ensure state compatibility during job updates.

❌ BAD
```java
DataStream<String> stream = env.fromElements("a", "b", "c");
stream.map(value -> value.toUpperCase());
```

✅ GOOD
```java
DataStream<String> stream = env.fromElements("a", "b", "c");
stream.map(value -> value.toUpperCase()).uid("map-uppercase-operator");
```

## Performance Considerations

### Monitor Consumer Lag and Checkpoint Duration
Regularly monitor consumer lag and checkpoint duration to maintain the health of your Flink jobs.

✅ GOOD
```java
env.getConfig().setAutoWatermarkInterval(100);
```

### Use State TTL
Implement state Time-To-Live (TTL) to prevent unbounded memory growth in stateful operations.

❌ BAD
```java
stateDescriptor.enableTimeToLive(null);
```

✅ GOOD
```java
ValueStateDescriptor<String> stateDescriptor = new ValueStateDescriptor<>("state", String.class);
stateDescriptor.enableTimeToLive(Time.days(1));
```

## Common Pitfalls and Gotchas

### Separate Refactoring from Feature Changes
Always separate refactoring from feature changes in different commits to maintain a clear project history.

❌ BAD
- Commit message: "Added feature X and refactored Y"

✅ GOOD
- Commit message 1: "Added feature X"
- Commit message 2: "Refactored Y for clarity"

### Choose Max Parallelism Wisely
Set max parallelism based on projected future scale to avoid costly state migration.

❌ BAD
```java
env.setParallelism(1);
```

✅ GOOD
```java
env.setParallelism(10); // Choose based on expected scale
```

## Testing Approaches

### Use Flink's Testing Utilities
Utilize Flink's built-in testing utilities to create reliable unit tests for your data processing logic.

✅ GOOD
```java
@Test
public void testMapFunction() throws Exception {
    StreamExecutionEnvironment env = StreamExecutionEnvironment.getExecutionEnvironment();
    DataStream<String> input = env.fromElements("a", "b", "c");
    DataStream<String> result = input.map(new MyMapFunction());

    List<String> output = result.executeAndCollect();
    assertThat(output).containsExactly("A", "B", "C");
}
```

### Document Method Contracts
Clearly document method contracts, but let code structure and descriptive naming explain the how.

✅ GOOD
```java
/**
 * Converts input string to uppercase.
 *
 * @param input the input string
 * @return the uppercase string
 */
public String toUpperCase(String input) {
    return input.toUpperCase();
}
```

By following these best practices, you can ensure that your Apache Flink applications are robust, maintainable, and scalable. Always prioritize clarity, performance, and reliability in your streaming pipelines.